This article is a joint press statement by President Obama and President Hu of China. The two leaders discussed various issues, including bilateral relations, major regional and international issues, economic cooperation, climate change, nonproliferation, and human rights. They expressed their commitment to building a positive and comprehensive relationship between the two countries and agreed to increase dialogue and cooperation. They also discussed the importance of maintaining open markets and free flows of commerce, as well as the need for both countries to play a role in addressing global challenges. The leaders also talked about the importance of resolving the Korean Peninsula nuclear issue and the Iranian nuclear issue through dialogue and negotiations. They highlighted the importance of respecting each other's sovereignty and territorial integrity and agreed to continue dialogue and exchanges on issues such as human rights and religion. The leaders emphasized the shared responsibility of both countries in preserving and promoting the growth of the China-U.S. relationship.